Material Culture "Teach-In" 
At a time of “post truth” and divisiveness in American culture, what can the study of historical artifacts offer? If every object is a fact in the world, perhaps artifacts have a role in anchoring discourse to reality? The close study of objects – the cultivation of material intelligence as a necessary aspect of scholarship – often provides insights into the past as well as embodiments of present-day debates. Can the engagement of an object in the past and in the present shed light on both contexts? 
Over a two-day event scholars are considering these complex questions. Drawing on the expertise of faculty, graduate students and museum staff from the Yale community, students gathered in the spirit of a “teach in” - pioneered in the late 1960s, when distrust of authority was commonplace in many American campus environments. Learning from one another in a non-hierarchical manner, and with no predetermined end goal, presenters posed ideas about the lives of objects, often in relation to particular artifacts or making processes. 
Here scholars conduct hands-on exercises to model methods of developing material intelligence as an aspect of pedagogy, research, and to examine the origins of cultural difference (and conflict) in production and process. Participants work ‘on the ground’ (with minimal equipment) vs a workbench to make spoons, as a standard and deceptively simple form, in clay, wood, and metal using traditional techniques of modeling, carving, hammering, and casting. The event was overseen by Edward Cooke (Yale History of Art); Carol Snow, Andres Garces and Paul Panamarenko (@yaleartgallery); Glenn Adamson (@yalebritishart); Jon Prown (@chipstone_org); Pamela Smith (@columbia); and many other faculty, graduate students, and museum people (curators, conservators, and educators) united by their interest in material literacy and interpretation.

# ( M N M E )

I’ve tried this throwing this latest batch of vases narrower than in previous attempts. These three bone dry cylinders will soon be bisquit fired along with another kiln load of work. As the years have gone by and taking photographs has become a greater part of what I do, I’ve certainly begun to appreciate how pots look in all their stages, it isn’t just about the finished pieces anymore. Showing how the pots look raw, leather hard, bone dry, bisque fired, glazed and finally fired are all aspects I try to capture beautifully. 
These are thrown with relatively stiff clay, while it’s definitely possible to do it with softer stuff, it can be a trickier process. I’m yet to try using a throwing stick when making these but they haven’t been a necessity yet. Instead I throw them with the tops flared out, as to fit my hand all the way to the bottom. Once all the bottom weight is pulled up I can then carefully collar in the higher sections of clay. Very well wedged clay and much coning is important with these, collaring in thin clay is just asking for trouble as it’ll want to twist and buckle. Sometimes it wont be too severe, but the rippled surface it leaves isn’t the most attractive, yet can be turned out if there’s enough clay.

Once leather hard I stick these back on the wheel by wetting the base of the vase before tap centring it and rubbing it against the metal wheel head, the water and friction causes it to stick thoroughly. There’s no need for a grip or three lumps of clay to hold it in place. I then carefully trim the outside edge to be as vertical as I can. While working I always hold onto the pot with my left hand, while my right grips the tool firmly, leaning my upper body weight on that arm to keep it steady. Turning really does require a great amount of sturdiness, my hand and whole arm are tensed to keep it rigid and secure. You want to turn through any slight wobbles or undulations, rather than letting them influence your turning.
